Machine: Apple M2 Pro, 32 GB, 200 GB/s
Date: 2026-05-03
Tool: mlx-bench (omlx sequential benchmark)
Prompt: "Write a 200-word introduction to quantum computing for a 10-year-old."
Max tokens: 512
Warmup: yes (warm tok/s reported)

Results:
  mlx-community__Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-4bit     45.89 tok/s  load: 9.72s
  mlx-community__Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-4bit-DWQ 45.36 tok/s  load: 7.35s
  mlx-community__Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-nvfp4    45.36 tok/s  load: 7.15s

Conclusion: All three quantization formats are bandwidth-bound on M2 Pro (200 GB/s).
No meaningful tok/s difference between std 4bit, DWQ-4bit, and NVFP4.
NVFP4 advantage seen on M5 (FP4 GPU accelerators) does not apply here.
DWQ and NVFP4 load ~2s faster than std 4bit (file structure difference).
Recommend: keep repo default (DWQ-4bit) on M2 Pro; switch to NVFP4 only on M5.
